Search queries can match many documents. Pagination lets you fetch and display results in chunks, keeping responses small and fast.

By default, Bleve returns the first 10 hits sorted by relevance (score), highest first.
Two pagination modes

    From/Size: simple and stateless; cost grows with page depth.
    SearchAfter/SearchBefore: efficient for deep paging; requires passing sort keys from the previous page.

Both modes can be used with any valid sort.
Size/From

Offset-based pagination uses Size (page length) and From (number of hits to skip). Bleve collects at least Size + From ordered results, then returns the Size slice starting at From.

JSON example:

{
  "query": { "match": "California" },
  "sort": ["-_score"],
  "size": 5,
  "from": 10
}

The result would be 5 hits starting from the 5th hit.

Total Sort Order

Pagination is deterministic. Ensure your Sort defines a total order, so that documents with the same sort keys are not left out:

    Sort strings can be field names (prefix with - for descending), "_score", or "_id".
    Always include a stable tie-breaker as the last key, typically "_id".
    Examples:
        ["country", "-age", "_id"]
        ["-_score", "_id"] (default score desc with a tie-breaker)

Performance guidance

    Offset pagination cost grows with From (collects at least Size + From results before slicing).




- Pagination should work on all pages except for Categorization
- Captions mode: Media Type should filter the caption media
- Search filtering should work across all modes without exiting that mode--but you could hide the searchbox on the Categorization page as that one doesn't really need it

Search mode should use xklb sorting for "Default" sort option:
PlayInOrder(lambda x: (
    # "video_count > 0 desc" — videos before audio-only
    -(int(bool(x.get("video_count")))),

    # "audio_count > 0 desc" — files with audio before silent ones
    -(int(bool(x.get("audio_count")))),

    # m.path like "http%" ASC — local files before remote URLs
    int((x.get("path") or "").startswith("http")),

    # "subtitle_count >0 desc" (random ~50/50 bias; pick the majority branch)
    -(int(bool(x.get("subtitle_count")))),

    # "play_count, playhead desc, time_last_played"
    # unplayed / least-played first
    x.get("play_count") or 0,
    # furthest along first (resume progress)
    -((x.get("playhead") or 0)),
    # least-recently played first
    x.get("time_last_played") or 0,

    # "title IS NOT NULL desc" — titled entries before untitled
    int(x.get("title") is None),

    # m.path ASC — alphabetical tiebreak
    x.get("path") or "",
  )
)

Or rather accept an array for complex sorting with drag-and-drop reordering. The functionality should expose a level of completeness which allows for the above

